      <h1 class="mb-8">The Precision Illusion: Why 6.3% Matters</h1>
      <div class="prose-page text-base leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-text)] space-y-4">
        <p>In our recent benchmark of LLM fitness advice, we found something surprising: <strong>0% overconfident outputs.</strong> The models weren't dangerously overconfident. They were subtly misleading.</p>
        <p>6.3% of outputs contained precise-sounding numerical claims — "a 38.7% reduction" — without any evidence grounding. We call this the <strong>precision illusion</strong>.</p>
        <p>Why does this matter? Because precise numbers carry disproportionate weight in human judgment. Zhang & Schwarz (2012) showed that people trust precise numbers more, even when they know the precision is unwarranted. A pseudo-precise output exploits this cognitive bias silently.</p>
        <p>At a 6.3% rate per output, a user session involving 10 advice statements carries a ~48% cumulative probability of encountering at least one pseudo-precise response. And these outputs cluster in exactly the scenarios where users most need reliable advice — mixed-evidence and insufficient-evidence questions.</p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
